No, apparently not. The creature just growled and tried to fly directly toward Thassalin. Fortunately, Thassalin, despite his size, was agile enough to dodge, but Nyssi let out a scream as she almost lost her grip on Thassalin's smooth scales.
„HOW CAN WE KILL HER?“, screamed Nyssi.
„AIM FOR THEIR HEADS!“
„THIS WILL BE DIFFICULT!“
Thassalin hissed and then drew a circle, moving closer to the mountain he called home. The dark beast followed, but became slightly panicked when a fire beam hit her from behind. She hadn't noticed she was no longer alone. She became even more panicked when Thassalin slowed down and then hurled his tail at her head, knocking her off course.
Snarling and growling, she flew upward and spat into the air. Everything suddenly became dark, as if the monster had sucked the light from the sky into itself and replaced it with a cloud of eternal night.
As he suddenly could no longer see anything, Thassalin tried to retreat. He felt himself scraping along the tree tops before he finally crashed into an open clearing. The beast seemed to know exactly where he had fallen, and shot directly at him, dragging the black cloud with it.
"Kayel!" shouted Tenuk as he slipped out of the cloud and began circling, searching in the darkness below for Nyssi and Thassalin. "What should we do now? Kayel…? Kayel, where are you?"
Below, Nyssi struggled to her feet. She was sure she had broken something, but her peculiar, supernatural healing powers were already beginning to take effect. Unfortunately, this did not apply to Thassalin. He leaned wearily against the only tree that had not collapsed under his weight. Nyssi made every effort to get close to Thassalin, but she could barely see two meters ahead. Everything was pitch black and shrouded in eerie shadows. And within this darkness, something screamed and screeched.
A terrifying, armored tail crashed beside Nyssi onto the ground and knocked her down. But she noticed that the tail was just swinging wildly and not attempting to hit her specifically. The beast—or what little Nyssi could see and hear of it—growled and clawed at the shadows it had created. Something shot through the darkness, stabbed at the monster, and confused it.
Suddenly, a gunshot cracked through the fog, and the monster fell silent, collapsed to the ground and lay motionless. The darkness around them faded, and they saw what had happened: On top of the beast stood Kayel, holding his rifle heavily panting.
“That was probably… the craziest shadow leap I've ever made… Thanto kat’olon…”, Kabel struggled for breath. His eyes glowed almost black, and a dark energy circled his body. But while he was still speaking, color returned to his armor, and his eyes regained their normal yellow color.
It took a moment for Nyssi to understand what had happened. They had all known that Kayel possessed these strange shadow powers. He used them rarely, because most found them eerie and quite frightening. But Nyssi had not known that Kayel could use these powers in any kind of darkness. And as Kayel behaved, he seemed to be quite surprised as well.
“Are you okay?” it came out of Nyssi.
“Yes, I'm fine. I've killed something, I'll be back to normal soon.” Kayel looked at his work, while Tenuk flew down, landed beside him, and resumed his normal spastic form.
Now that the beast was no longer moving, they could better see what it was. Its skin was pitch-black and slimy, but the slime stayed stuck to its body. It had four wings and four limbs, all ending in long, thin claws, and two straight horns stood out from its skull.
Before Tenuk and Kayel could ask what the hell they were looking at, something screeched and leaped out from a nearby bush. It didn't get to them, however, because a familiar vehicle crashed into its side and caused the monster to slide to a stop in front of Nyssi's feet. Nyssi wanted to take no risks. She grabbed her shotgun, fired without thinking at its head, and the creature died right there.
“Oops…”, murmured Retvik from the driver's seat, before awkwardly turning off the engine and stepping out of the truck. “Uh, that was actually not intended. Are you all okay?”
“You missed all the action,” scolded Tenuk. “Where were you?”
“You all just left me standing. I came as fast as I could…”, sighed Retvik. “May I ask what those terrible creatures are?”
Retvik's question was fortunately answered by Thassalin, who had regained his composure. He was covered in cuts and scratches and seemed a bit dazed, but not seriously injured.
„YOU HAVE KILLED THE CORRUPTED! THE INFECTED MONSTERS. BEINGS THAT WERE LEAVING HERE, WHEN THE CORRUPTION ATTACKED YOUR GODS.“
„You mean the terrible God-Monster-being, that we… helped kill?“, stammered Tenuk.
„YES. EXACTLY THAT. Perhaps there are more. But I could not shoot into the head. I have no gun. And two against one is unfair, or?“ Thassalin hobbled to Kayel and patted his head. „THANK YOU, LITTLE ONE. YOU REMIND ME OF MY OLD FRIEND ARKADIN. JUST NOT SO MURDEROUS AND NOT SO SKILLED IN KILLING ENTIRE UNIVERSES.“
„Um… thank you… I think…“, shrugged Kayel. „So, are we done here?“
Nyssi shrugged her shoulders. She grabbed her camera and took a few photos of the now definitely dead creatures. Then she pulled out her favorite weapon, the ornate Death God dagger, and began sawing off one of the creature's horns. Afterwards, she moved on to the second. But as Nyssi was just finished, the creatures suddenly burst into flames and turned into a pile of ash in seconds. The same happened to the horns Nyssi had cut off.
"So, that's both practical and impractical at the same time…," sighed Nyssi. "But at least I have the photos, hopefully."
